# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1886-st-louis-maroons-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons** baseball team finished with a 94–19 record and won the championship of the new Union Association (UA).
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] After the season, the UA folded and the Maroons joined the National League; they were the only UA team to continue past the 1884 season.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] To this day, the Maroons' .832 winning percentage hasn't been matched by a professional baseball team.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons are not usually mentioned in the conversation of baseball teams with the best single-season records of all time.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] This team also set the record for the best start to a season in baseball history, going 20–0 before losing 8–1 to the Boston Reds on May 24, in their 21st game of the season.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The Maroons scored 887 runs while allowing 429, for a run differential of +458, the best in major-league history, as records and statistics of the UA are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1884-st-louis-maroons-season] The team was back in the news in 2015, when the Golden State Warriors started the 2015–16 season with an NBA-record 24 straight wins; this surpassed the Maroons' 20–0 start, which was previously the record for the four major professional sports leagues in the United States.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1885-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons season** was the team's first season in the National League after winning the Union Association championship in 1884.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1885-st-louis-maroons-season] This season was not nearly as successful, as the Maroons finished with a 36–72 record, worst in the eight-team league.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1886 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 16th season of the franchise.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1886 Brooklyn Grays season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The team finished the season in third place with a record of 76–61 (their first winning season), 16 games behind the St.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1886 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 15th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 11th in the National League and the second at the first West Side Park.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished first in the National League with a record of 90–34, 2.5 games ahead of the second place Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was defeated four games to two by the St.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings lost the 1886 World Series to the St.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] Louis Maroons** finished with a 43–79 record in the National League, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] After the season, the team was purchased by John T.
[src:1886-st-louis-maroons-season/1886-st-louis-maroons-season] Brush and moved to Indianapolis, becoming the **Hoosiers**.
